In a college project, trying multiple models is normal because the goal is to compare algorithms and learn which one performs best.

In a real client project, you usually don't do it that way.

Real Industry Approach
----------------------

A typical workflow is:

Understand Business Problem
        ↓
Analyze Data
        ↓
Select 1–3 Suitable Models
        ↓
Train & Evaluate
        ↓
Choose Best Model
        ↓
Deploy

===========

For example, if a client wants stock-price forecasting:

| Situation                  | Model Choice |
| -------------------------- | ------------ |
| Simple trend forecasting   | ARIMA        |
| Short-term time series     | AR / ARIMA   |
| Complex nonlinear patterns | LSTM         |
| Seasonal data              | SARIMA       |

========

An experienced data scientist doesn't randomly try 20 models. They narrow it down quickly based on:

Dataset size
Data pattern
Business requirement
Time available
Accuracy requirement
